response:
 Since $g$ is odd and satisfies $g(-n) = -g(n)$ for all $n$ in the domain of $g$, and since the cube function $ i \rightarrow i^3 $ is odd, $g$ composed with this function is odd, i.e.,
\begin{align*}
    g(-n^3) &= -g(n^3)
\end{align*}
Now, $s \bmod 2 = s$. So we can show that $g$ composed with the function $x \rightarrow x^3$ is odd:
\begin{align*}
    g(-(n^3)^3) &= g(-n^9) \\
    &= -g(n^9) &&\text{(since $x \rightarrow x^3$ is odd)} \\
    &= -g((-n)^3) &&\text{(since $n \rightarrow n^3$ is even)} \\
    &= -g(-(n^3)) &&\text {(since $g$ is odd)} \\
    &= -g(-n^3) &&\text{(since $x \rightarrow x^3$ is odd)}.
\end{align*}
factoring out $(-1)^3$:
\begin{align*}
    g(-(n^3)^3) &= -(-1)^3 g(n^3) \\
    &= (-1)^{3+1} g(n^3) &&\text{(since $-1$ is odd)} \\
    &= (-1)^4 g(n^3) &&\text{(since $3+1 = 4$)} \\
    &= (-1) g(n^3) &&\text{(since $(-1)^4 = -1$)} \\
    &= -g(n^3)
\end{align*}
but $n \mapsto n^3$ is odd, so $g \circ (i \mapsto i^3)$ is even, i.e.,
\begin{align*}
    g(-(n^3)^3) &= -g((-(n^3))^3) \\
    g(-(n^3)^3) &= g((-(n^3))^3) && \text{(since $g \circ (-1)$ is odd, i.e., } -g(-n) = g(n) \text{: see }\textit{here}\text{)}
\end{align*}
so, 
\begin{align*}
    g(-n^3) &= g(-(n^3)^3) \\
\end{align*}
and therefore, $g \circ (i \mapsto i^3)$ is even.
Since $|n|$ is even if $n = 0$, the function $h(n) = |n|$ is even. Since $|g \circ (i \mapsto i^3)| = h(g \circ (i \mapsto i^3))$, $f$ is even, as claimed.
